    slug: "jaanshini-ka-haq-new",
    description: `Jaanshini Ka Haq (New Edition) is an Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the important topic of inheritance rights in Islam, specifically focusing on the rights of heirs (jaanshini) and the detailed Islamic rulings governing the distribution of a deceased person's estate. The title "Jaanshini Ka Haq" translates to "The Right of the Heir," and the new edition of this book represents an updated and expanded treatment of a subject that is both practically essential and frequently misunderstood within Muslim communities. Inheritance law (ilm al-fara'id) is one of the most precisely defined areas of Islamic jurisprudence, with the Quran itself prescribing the shares of various heirs in Surah An-Nisa (Chapter 4), earning it the title "the half of knowledge" due to its complexity and importance.

The book begins by establishing the Islamic foundation for inheritance, explaining why Islam has prescribed specific shares for specific heirs rather than leaving the distribution of wealth entirely to individual discretion. The author draws upon the Quranic verses in Surah An-Nisa that establish the inheritance framework, demonstrating how these divine prescriptions serve the purposes of justice, fairness, the protection of vulnerable family members, the prevention of wealth concentration, and the maintenance of family cohesion after the death of a loved one. The book explains that the Islamic inheritance system was revolutionary when it was revealed, as it granted inheritance rights to women, children, and other relatives who had no such rights in pre-Islamic Arabian society, and it continues to represent one of the most equitable systems of wealth transfer ever devised.

The core of the book provides a detailed and systematic explanation of the Islamic inheritance rules, covering every category of heir recognised by Islamic law. These include the fixed-share heirs (ashab al-furud) such as the husband, wife, father, mother, daughters, granddaughters, full sisters, paternal sisters, maternal sisters, and grandfather, each of whom receives a specific fraction or fraction-range of the estate as prescribed by the Quran. The book also covers the male agnate heirs (asabah) who inherit whatever remains after the fixed shares are distributed, including sons, sons of sons, full brothers, paternal brothers, and paternal uncles. The author explains the rules governing cases where the total of the fixed shares exceeds the estate (a situation known as 'awl or proportionate reduction), cases where no fixed-share heir exists and the entire estate goes to the asabah, and the complex rules of inheritance by blocking (hajb) where the presence of certain heirs prevents other heirs from receiving anything. The book includes practical worked examples and calculation tables that help readers understand how the inheritance shares are computed in real-world scenarios involving different combinations of heirs.

The new edition includes expanded coverage of several topics that have become increasingly relevant in contemporary Muslim communities, including the inheritance rights of adopted children, the distribution of inheritance in cases of mixed marriages between Muslims and non-Muslims, the status of life insurance policies and pension schemes under Islamic inheritance law, the rules governing the distribution of digital assets and intellectual property, and the role of Islamic wills (wasiyyah) within the inheritance framework. The book also addresses common practices and customs that contradict the Islamic inheritance rules, such as the disinheritance of daughters, the preferential treatment of eldest sons, and the failure to distribute the estate promptly after death, explaining why these practices are religiously prohibited and socially harmful. Written in clear and accessible Urdu, this book serves as both a practical reference guide and an educational resource for families, scholars, legal professionals, and anyone who wants to understand and implement the Islamic inheritance system correctly.`,
