    slug: "jadoo-ki-haqeeqat",
    description: `Jadoo Ki Haqeeqat (The Reality of Magic and Sorcery) is an Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a comprehensive, scholarly examination of the Islamic perspective on magic (sihr), sorcery, witchcraft, and the occult, drawing upon the Quran, the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the consensus of classical Islamic scholars to separate what is real and religiously acknowledged from what is myth, superstition, and cultural fabrication. The title "Jadoo Ki Haqeeqat" literally means "The Reality of Magic," and the book sets out to establish exactly what Islam teaches about this subject, addressing a topic that is widely discussed in Muslim communities but often poorly understood, frequently exaggerated, and sometimes deliberately exploited for personal gain.

The book begins by establishing the foundational Islamic position on magic and sorcery, which is that magic is real, that it exists as a phenomenon in the world, and that it is categorically prohibited (haram) in Islam. The author presents the evidence from the Quran, including the verses in Surah Al-Baqarah (2:102) that describe how the angels Harut and Marut taught magic to the people of Babylon as a test, and the verses that describe how the sorcerers of Pharaoh were defeated by the miracles of Prophet Musa (Moses), peace be upon him. The book also draws upon the hadith narrations in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) acknowledged the reality of magic, including the famous incident involving the Jewish sorcerer Labid ibn al-A'sam who cast a spell on the Prophet, and the hadith that lists magic among the major sins that destroy a person's religion. The author carefully explains the Islamic definition of magic, distinguishing it from illusion, sleight of hand, and tricks (which are not considered true magic in the religious sense), and clarifying the different types of magic recognised in Islamic jurisprudence, including separative magic (sihr al-tafriq), love magic (sihr al-mahabbah), magic that causes illness, and magic that creates delusions and hallucinations.

A major portion of the book is devoted to distinguishing between authentic Islamic teachings about magic and the widespread superstitions, cultural practices, and fraudulent claims that plague many Muslim communities. The author identifies and refutes numerous common beliefs and practices that have no basis in Islam, including the belief that certain stones, amulets, or talismans can ward off magic, the practice of visiting self-proclaimed spiritual healers who claim to remove magic for money, the use of fortune-telling and astrology as supposed remedies, the belief in evil eye as a form of magic that requires elaborate rituals to cure, and the many folk practices involving nails, hair, blood, and animal sacrifice that are wrongly attributed to Islamic tradition. For each of these practices, the author provides the Islamic ruling, explains why it is incorrect or prohibited, and offers the authentic Islamic alternative. The book then provides a detailed and practical guide to protection from magic according to the authentic Sunnah, including the recitation of Surah Al-Falaq and Surah An-Nas, the recitation of Ayat al-Kursi, the morning and evening adhkar, the specific du'as taught by the Prophet for protection, the use of ruqyah (spiritual healing through Quranic recitation) for those who have been affected by magic, and the importance of maintaining strong faith, regular prayer, and trust in Allah as the ultimate protection against all forms of harm. Written in clear, scholarly Urdu with full references, this book is an essential guide for anyone seeking to understand the Islamic perspective on magic and protect themselves and their families through authentic means.`,
    metaDescription: "Jadoo Ki Haqeeqat is an Urdu Islamic book examining the reality of magic in Islam, refuting superstitions, and offering authentic Sunnah-based protections."
