    slug: "maarka-e-qadsiyah-kay-sunehray-waqiyaat",
    description: `Maarka-e-Qadsiyah Kay Sunehray Waqiyaat (The Golden Events of the Battle of Qadisiyyah) is an Urdu-language Islamic history book that provides a vivid and detailed narrative of the Battle of Qadisiyyah, one of the most decisive and consequential military engagements in Islamic history, fought between the Muslim army and the Sassanid Persian Empire in the year 15 AH (636 CE). The title "Sunehray Waqiyaat" (Golden Events) reflects the author's intention to present the battle not merely as a military historical event but as a chapter in the glorious history of Islam that contains golden lessons of faith, courage, leadership, and divine assistance that continue to inspire Muslims today. The Battle of Qadsiyyah is widely regarded as one of the most significant battles in world history, as it resulted in the collapse of the Sassanid Persian Empire — one of the two great superpowers of the ancient world — and opened the door to the spread of Islam across Persia, Central Asia, and eventually the Indian subcontinent.

The book begins by providing the historical context that led to the Battle of Qadisiyyah, explaining the relationship between the Muslim state in Madinah and the Sassanid Persian Empire, the failed Muslim expedition to Iraq during the caliphate of Abu Bakr al-Siddiq, and the strategic decisions made by the second caliph, Umar ibn al-Khattab (may Allah be pleased with him), to launch a full-scale military campaign against the Persians. The author describes the political situation within the Sassanid Empire, including the internal power struggles, the military strength of the Persian army, and the personality and leadership style of the Persian commander Rustam Farrukhzad. The book also covers the appointment of Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas as the Muslim commander, the composition and size of the Muslim army, and the strategic planning that preceded the battle.

The core of the book provides a detailed, day-by-day narrative of the battle, which lasted for approximately three to four days and involved some of the most dramatic and memorable episodes in Islamic military history. The author describes the initial skirmishes and the failed negotiations between the two sides, the ferocious combat on the first day in which the Muslim archers played a decisive role, the events of the second day when the Persian war elephants nearly broke the Muslim lines, the brilliant tactical innovation of the Muslim soldiers who devised a method to neutralise the elephants, the pivotal third day when the Muslim cavalry launched a devastating counterattack, and the final day when the Persians were decisively defeated and their commander Rustam was killed. The book presents these events in a dramatic narrative style that brings the battle to life, using the descriptions recorded by the early Muslim historians while maintaining historical accuracy.

Throughout the narrative, the author highlights the spiritual dimensions of the battle, showing how the faith, courage, and reliance on Allah of the Muslim soldiers were the decisive factors in their victory against a numerically and materially superior enemy. The book includes the famous du'as that Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas recited during the battle, the speeches and exhortations of the Muslim commanders before each day's fighting, the individual acts of heroism performed by the companions and their successors, and the various miracles and divine signs that the Muslims witnessed during the course of the battle. The book also includes a detailed analysis of the military tactics employed by both sides, comparing the Persian strategy of relying on war elephants, heavy cavalry, and fortified positions with the Muslim approach of mobility, archery, and disciplined infantry formations. The aftermath of the battle is covered as well, including the Muslim advance into the Sassanid capital of Ctesiphon (Mada'in), the fall of the Persian Empire, and the long-term consequences of the Muslim victory for the spread of Islam and the course of world history. Written in engaging and descriptive Urdu with references to the classical Arabic historical sources, this book is both an informative history and an inspiring account of one of Islam's greatest military achievements.`,
    metaDescription: "Maarka-e-Qadsiyah Kay Sunehray Waqiyaat is an Urdu history book detailing the decisive Battle of Qadisiyyah with vivid narration and Islamic lessons."
