    slug: "maeeshat-o-tijarat-ka-islami-ahkam",
    description: `Maeeshat-o-Tijarat Ka Islami Ahkam (Islamic Rulings on Livelihood and Commerce) is a comprehensive Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a detailed and systematic guide to the Islamic laws, principles, and ethics governing business, trade, employment, and financial transactions. The book addresses one of the most practically important areas of Islamic jurisprudence (fiqh al-mu'amalat), covering every aspect of economic life from the individual's choice of livelihood to the complex transactions of modern commerce, all within the framework of Islamic law as derived from the Quran, the authentic Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the established principles of Islamic jurisprudence developed by the classical scholars. This book is written for Urdu-speaking Muslims who are engaged in business, commerce, or professional life and who wish to ensure that their economic activities are conducted in full compliance with Islamic teachings.

The book is divided into several major sections, each addressing a different dimension of Islamic economic life. The opening section establishes the foundational Islamic principles that govern all economic activity, including the principle that all sustenance (rizq) comes from Allah, the obligation to earn a lawful (halal) livelihood, the prohibition of interest (riba) in all its forms, the requirement of honesty and transparency in all transactions, the prohibition of fraud and deception (gharar), the importance of fulfilling contracts and agreements, and the Islamic view of wealth as a trust (amanah) from Allah that must be used responsibly and ethically. The author supports each principle with relevant Quranic verses and hadith narrations, providing the religious foundation upon which the practical rulings of the book are built.

The section on business transactions (buyu') covers the Islamic rulings on all major types of commercial transactions, including cash sales, credit sales, advance payments (salam), manufacturing orders (istisna'), joint ventures (musharakah), agency relationships (wakalah), guaranteeing transactions (kafalah), and pawn transactions (rahn). For each type of transaction, the author explains the conditions that must be met for the transaction to be Islamically valid, the common mistakes and violations that people make, and the practical steps that businesspeople can take to ensure their dealings are compliant. The section also addresses specific business practices that are prohibited in Islam, including cheating in weights and measures, selling defective goods without disclosure, hoarding (ihtikar) essential commodities to artificially inflate prices, bid-rigging (najsh), and the creation of artificial scarcity. The section on employment and professional life covers the Islamic rulings on the employer-employee relationship, including the obligation to pay workers promptly and fairly, the prohibition of exploiting workers, the rights of employees to rest, safety, and respectful treatment, the Islamic ruling on working in industries or professions that involve prohibited activities (such as alcohol, gambling, or interest-based finance), and the ethics of professional conduct.

The book includes dedicated sections on contemporary economic issues that are of particular relevance to modern Muslims, including Islamic banking and finance, insurance (takaful vs. conventional insurance), stock market investments, online business and e-commerce, cryptocurrency, credit cards and loans, mortgages, and the Islamic perspective on modern economic systems such as capitalism and socialism. For each contemporary issue, the author presents the views of the major Islamic scholars and institutions, explains the reasoning behind their rulings, and provides practical guidance for Muslims navigating these complex topics. The book also includes a section on the Islamic ethics of wealth, covering the obligation of zakat, the virtue of charity (sadaqah), the Islamic teaching on moderation in spending, and the dangers of materialism and greed. Written in clear and scholarly Urdu, this book is an essential reference for Muslim businesspeople, professionals, students of Islamic finance, and anyone who wants to conduct their economic life in accordance with Islamic principles.`,
    metaDescription: "Maeeshat-o-Tijarat Ka Islami Ahkam is an Urdu guide to Islamic business law, commerce ethics, and modern financial rulings from Quran and Sunnah."
