    slug: "mera-jeena-mera-marna",
    description: `Mera Jeena Mera Marna (My Life, My Death) is a profound Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the fundamental questions of human existence — the purpose of life, the reality of death, and what lies beyond — from the perspective of Islamic teachings, drawing upon the Quran, the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the wisdom of the classical Islamic scholars to present a comprehensive and deeply moving exploration of these existential themes. The title "Mera Jeena Mera Marna" captures the essence of the book's scope: it examines the entire human journey from the moment of conception through life, death, and the Hereafter, helping the reader understand not only what Islam teaches about these topics but why these teachings are essential for living a meaningful, purposeful, and spiritually fulfilling life. The book is written for Urdu-speaking Muslims who are seeking to understand the bigger picture of their existence and to align their lives with the ultimate purpose for which Allah created them.

The book begins with a thorough discussion of the Islamic understanding of the purpose of human existence, establishing from the Quran that human beings were created for the purpose of worshipping and knowing Allah (Surah Adh-Dhariyat 51:56). The author explains that this purpose encompasses not merely ritual worship but the entire spectrum of human activity — work, relationships, recreation, intellectual pursuits, and emotional experiences — all of which can be transformed into acts of worship when performed with the right intention and in accordance with Islamic guidance. The book draws upon the hadith qudsi in which Allah says: "I was a hidden treasure, and I loved to be known, so I created creation so that I would be known," explaining how this divine saying illuminates the deepest purpose behind human existence and the relationship between the Creator and His creation.

The section on life (Jeena) covers the Islamic perspective on every major aspect of human existence, including the nature of the soul (ruh) and its connection to the body, the Islamic concept of the stages of life (the stages of the womb, childhood, youth, maturity, and old age), the tests and trials that every human being faces, the concepts of qadar (divine decree) and ikhtiyar (human free will), the Islamic approach to happiness and contentment, the role of suffering and hardship in spiritual growth, the importance of preparing for the Hereafter while living fully in the present world, and the Islamic teachings on time management, priorities, and the balanced life. The author provides practical guidance on how to live each day with purpose and awareness, drawing upon the hadith in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) said: "Be in this world as though you were a stranger or a traveller," and the advice of the early Muslim scholars who viewed this life as a mere stopping point on the journey to eternity.

The section on death (Marna) provides a detailed and unflinching examination of the reality of death as described in the Islamic texts, covering the physical process of dying, the experience of the soul at the moment of death, the angels of death and the different receptions that await the righteous and the disobedient souls, the washing and shrouding of the body, the Islamic funeral prayer, the burial, and the beginning of the journey into the Hereafter. The book discusses the questioning in the grave by the two angels Munkar and Nakir, the bliss or punishment of the grave, and the intermediate state (barzakh) between death and the Day of Resurrection. The section on the Hereafter covers the Day of Judgment, the scales of deeds, the bridge over Hell (Sirat), the intercession of the Prophet, and the ultimate destinations of Paradise and the Hellfire, all presented with references to the authentic Quranic descriptions and hadith narrations. The book concludes with practical guidance on how to prepare for death and the Hereafter, including the importance of repentance, good deeds, regular charity, maintaining family ties, and keeping one's spiritual accounts in order. Written in eloquent and deeply reflective Urdu, this book is a powerful reminder of the realities that every human being must eventually face, and a guide for living a life that is prepared for them.`,
